<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-06-09T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-06-09T06:00:00-05:00" n="657" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d657">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00114A Pacific War/496:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Standley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-09T14:00:00+03:00">June
                                        9, 1943—2 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received 7:39 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>630. Department’s 365, May 26, 9 p.m., last paragraph. Foreign Office
                                states that a reply to the question concerning the several alternate
                                routes for the movement of supplies to American and Allied nationals
                                detained by the Japs will be given as soon as the American
                                Government receives an answer from the Japanese Government on the
                                question.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Standley</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>